    <title>Borges, Escher, &amp; Origami Tessellations</title>
    <content type='html'>The Argentinian writer &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jorge_Luis_Borges"&gt;Jorge Luis Borges&lt;/a&gt; is a favorite of mathematics enthusiasts - many of his short stories and essays have overtly mathematical themes, and much of his writing plays with structure and paradox in a way that appeals to readers that have a mathematical bent (see &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Borges_and_mathematics"&gt;this Wikipedia article&lt;/a&gt; on Borges and mathematics).&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I just recently read his short-story collection, a &lt;b&gt;Universal History of Iniquity&lt;/b&gt;, which does not have any direct mathematical overtones (that I can recall), but whose cover in the Penguin Classics edition plays homage to Borges' mathematical ways with one of &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M._C._Escher"&gt;M.C. Escher&lt;/a&gt;'s limit engravings &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snakes_(M._C._Escher)"&gt;&lt;i&gt;Snakes&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgV7zn0O76Lc9eCcB29B-9w92gjC9ESxNsAc-6CRj4tFBEXY-R_MLmILuq6-DqXFysdKdMfBHSNABHafA7laTC66-uEN_SR9nXc7R9shPoEh_E7KPDNdeWxOgj8hG3C41mvarGGeyp4Fjk/s1600/iniquity1.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" height="400" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgV7zn0O76Lc9eCcB29B-9w92gjC9ESxNsAc-6CRj4tFBEXY-R_MLmILuq6-DqXFysdKdMfBHSNABHafA7laTC66-uEN_SR9nXc7R9shPoEh_E7KPDNdeWxOgj8hG3C41mvarGGeyp4Fjk/s1600/iniquity1.jpg" width="248" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
In keeping with the mathematical theme, a &amp;nbsp;new cover for the same book features the origami&amp;nbsp;tessellations&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="http://www.origamitessellations.com/"&gt;Eric Gjerde&lt;/a&gt; (see his post about the cover &lt;a href="http://www.origamitessellations.com/2012/10/cover-images-for-jorge-luis-borges/"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEi59ejLqpCgIBmZGvtUMOIVAiNptSPPCkQRipCDZuLlk1ctH1RxyVSS0l-tE5s87scHWjnVUBAsCKhVwZLENxW5pKA3IHCtE7cfUhoKT2IUdwwodUeLCGAJavByfYHe8m3BEH3WOk7TrmU/s1600/infamy.JPG" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" height="400" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEi59ejLqpCgIBmZGvtUMOIVAiNptSPPCkQRipCDZuLlk1ctH1RxyVSS0l-tE5s87scHWjnVUBAsCKhVwZLENxW5pKA3IHCtE7cfUhoKT2IUdwwodUeLCGAJavByfYHe8m3BEH3WOk7TrmU/s1600/infamy.JPG" width="283" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The&amp;nbsp;tessellation&amp;nbsp;is Gjerde's water-bomb tessellation, and is one of the more easily folded models from his &lt;a href="http://books.google.com/books/about/Origami_Tessellations.html?id=4NQmAQAAMAAJ"&gt;book&lt;/a&gt;. See &lt;a href="http://www.happyfolding.com/instructions-gjerde-water_bomb"&gt;this video on Happy Folding&lt;/a&gt; for a demo of how to make the water-bomb tessellation - it&amp;nbsp;is fun to fold, and can be playfully integrated into other origami projects... for example,&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="http://bethorigami.wordpress.com/"&gt;Beth Johnson&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;has turned it into a&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="http://bethorigami.wordpress.com/origami/designs/sheep-3/"&gt;sheep&lt;/a&gt;.</content>
